column168: During loading activities at the terminal, 1- 55 gallon drum of UN1263 Paint was punctured by other freight and released 25 gallons to the trailer floor. Terminal employees over packed the drum and cleaned up the impacted trailer floor with absorbents. The over pack was staged on site pending shipper instructions.

During a routine walk through inspection at the Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. in-transit 10 -day storage facility at Lake Point, UT a leaking drum was discovered. The drum was discovered to have a seeping leak on the bottom seam/weld area resulting in a release of material. Facility management was notified and an in house crew responded. The response crew donned the proper PPE, over-packed the damaged drum and clean up debris into a suitable salvage drum, and secured the drum for continued transportation to the intended disposal facility. The Utah Department of Environmental Quality was notified. Utah DEQ operator Chris provided report #12348.
column169: At the time the driver initiated transportation activities no evidence of leaking was observed. The seeping in the drum appeard to be the result of corrosion on the interior of the drum's bottom surface. The shipper was advised of the incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity. The driver was re-instructed to perform a thorough inspection of all containers prior to accepting them for transportation and to reject any containers with suspect integrity.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: September 3, 2015:  At approximately 9:00AM, while performing a routine inspection of railcars, CR Car Inspector noted tank car NATX 33544, residue last containing Petroleum Gases, Liquefied, with frost on the protective housing and partially down the side of the car.  Car Inspector reported his observation to CR Trainmaster P. Delisi, who in turn contacted CR Risk Management-Hazmat A. Richter.    CR emergency response contractor Hepaco responded to investigate and remediate.  Inspection noted the shipper's seal still intact on the protective housing securement pin, which he removed to open the housing's lid.  Further inspection found both liquid valves partially frosted around the closure plugs (plug-style valves) and vapor also being emitted from the vapor valve.  Valves were not properly closed, whereby closing them stopped the leaks.  After defrosting the valves, Hepaco noted all closure plugs were not even hand tight (required to be tool tight).  Car secured, frosting both inside and outside the protective housing was cleared and car was okay to be shipped to destination.

column168: On September 3, 2015 at 17:09 at hours, FRA Haz-Mat Inspector Ryan Tabor reported GATX 2599, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., was venting from the vacuum relief valve, the secondary securement plug on the vapor line valve was less than tool tight, and six of the manyway cover securement bolt washers were damaged.  The car was isolated and the consignee, Valero Marketing + Supply, was notified via CHEMTREC Report # 2015-0903-00294. Summit, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor release due to a damaged O-ring on the valve seat of the vacuum relief valve.  The vacuum relief valve was removed from the car and replaced with 2.5 pipe plug and the vapor line valve plug was secured.  The issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to Valeros representative (Robert Buchek).  The car was held out of transportation pending repair and qualification and/or issuance of a One Time Movement Approval from the FRA.  A special switching move was required.      NARRI: 5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70  Cause Code: 1095    On September 3, 2015 at 17:09 at hours, FRA Haz-Mat Inspector Ryan Tabor reported CTCX 731257, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., was venting from the manway cover and that the secondary securement plug on the vapor line valve was less than tool tight.  The car was isolated and the consignee, Valero Marketing + Supply, was notified via CHEMTREC Report # 2015-0903-00294. Summit, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor release due to a damaged manway cover gasket.  The manway cover gasket was replaced and the vapor line valve plug secured.  The issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to Valeros representative (Robert Buchek).  The car was released for transportation.      NARRI: 5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70  Cause Code: 209

column168: On September 3rd, 2015 at 00:31 hours, personnel in the CSXT Selkirk Yard discovered CBTX 742701, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car, to have wetness down the sides of the tank car coming from the top fitting area. The tank car was isolated and the Shipper, UET Shipping, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-09-03-00008. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont, the Glenmont branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was from the liquid line valve, the valve body was not tight on the thread nipple flange plate, as product was bypassing the connection point of the valve body to the threaded nipple and dripping onto the tank car. EPSVT tightened the valve body  of a turn and the release was secured, CBTX 742701 was staged for 2 hours to verify no further release, the valve box cover was re-sealed and car was released.  Mr. Clarence Vassau, office: was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. CBTX 742701 was released for transport.    This incident did NOT require a special move.    Cause Code: 282 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

column168: Truck Operator was driving eastbound to Show Low, AZ on Hwy 260 during early morning hours.  He had just gone through Heber-Overgaard, AZ and was on the eastern side of the city between mile marker 309-310 traveling 46 mph, when operator reported swerving to the right to miss an elk, slamming the guard rail and riding on top of it and over it.  This brought the tractor & trailer onto the shoulder and 5-10' down an embankment.  Operator tried to coming back on the road with the truck riding the guardrail and top of the 15-20' cement culvert/wash.  The trailer went airborn, jumping most of the culvert.  The end of the trailer's passenger side collided violently with the eastern side of the culvert causing the overturn.  The truck and trailer both overturned 270 degrees coming to rest on the driver's side.  Tractor and Trailer remained connected.  There was a spill of approximately 146 gallons of unleaded gasoline which was lost with the 4' breach in the #4 rear compartment of the trailer.  Emergency personnel were on scene with 8 minutes and booms and dikes were setup to catch any possible leakage beyond the initial release of 146 gallons.
column169: Driver has been through company provided training regarding never to swerve for animals, but to hold your lane.  He admitted knowing what he was supposed to do, but was unable to not swerve in the moment when the elk ran in front of him.  Continued training will occur.

column168: At approximately 2200 hours on Saturday, September 12, 2015, tank car TILX 101035 was reported leaking from the manway area.  M&M Protection, LLC was dispatched to the scene. M&M personnel determined that the leak was coming from the flange on the 2" liquid line valve. Two of the four bolts were loose and had seized up preventing further tightening. M&M stopped the leak at 2300 hours by relieving pressure on the car and venting to atmosphere. The car was isolated in Pasadena yard until repairs to the bolts could be made. On Monday, September 14 M&M was able to get the proper tools to repair the seized bolts and tighten the bolts to the proper specs for movement to customer. The car was then moved to Eco Services at PTRA Manchester Yard, approx. 4.5 miles to be unloaded.

column168: The tank was given a visual prefill inspection and a Ferrell meter test by the driver prior to the start of the filling process. The container was maintaining its internal pressure at the time with no signs of any leak. The upper tank shell failure resulted in two holes in the upper tank area where the done/lid rest and were roughly 1/4" in one hole and 3/4" in the other. At the time of the failure and uncontrolled release of product the driver activated the emergency shutoff device to shut off the bobtail and closed the hose end valve to stop the flow of gas into the tank. About 17 gallons of propane blew out into the air and dissipated. There were no injuries and no property damage.
column169: Always complete a thorough pre fill visual inspection before filling.

column168: During unloading operations it was discovered that approximately 1 gallon of a UN1263 Flammable paint was released from a 55 gallon metal drum to the wooden freight trailer floor only. An apparent forklift puncture resulted in the release. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the release. Terminal personnel over packed the damaged drum and staged it on site pending the shipper's disposition. Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted area. All wastes were collected, containerized and staged on site for pending disposal.

column168: During offloading operations, it was discovered that 2-5 gallon metal jerricans containing a UN1263 Flammable paint were punctured by an apparent forklift resulting in the release of approximately 6 gallons to the wooden freight trailer floor only. 1-5 gallon jerrican released all 5 gallons & 1-5 jerrican released 1 gallon. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the release. An environmental contractor was dispatched and over packed the damaged container and staged it on site pending the shipper's disposition. Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted area. All wastes were collected, containerized and staged on site for pending disposal.

column168: At 05:17 hours on September 18, 2015, a Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) employee reported an odor coming from one of two loaded tank cars in the KCS Port Arthur, TX yard.  KCS Environmental + Hazmat Department dispatched an emergency response contractor to investigate.  The shipper was notified and also sent a responder to the yard to assist with investigation.      The responders assessed the UTLX 930080 and found no leak or defects. They then assessed the UTLX 900549. There was very low readings of H2S in the protective housing (less than 5ppm), but nothing obvious, and non-detect readings on the ground and outside the protective housing. The fittings and valves were tested with snoop (a bubble solution) and responders located a very small, minuet, leak from the B-end Liquid Line Valve at the base plate connection. There was one loose B-end liquid valve connection nut which was tightened securing the leak (1/2 turn loose). More snoop was applied to verify that the leak had been secured.    The UTLX 900549 was returned to the shipper's plant under a one time movement approval 3 for unloading, root cause investigation, and recertification.     File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: An unrelated transportation accident on opposite side of freeway caused traffic in front of our truck to slow down rapidly. Our truck was unable to slow down fast enough and therefore attempted to navigate onto right shoulder in an effort to avoid rear end collision. The rear axle of secondary trailer locked its breaks and caused a violent enough action to cause roll over. The roll over caused large dents on the left side of cargo tank, that will require repair. No cargo was released during this event.
column169: After a thorough investigation it was determined that our driver could have begun reducing his speed sooner upon noticing emergency response activity which may have allowed him more time to avoid the incident. The associated driver is required to take a Defensive Driver refresher course and has been placed on 90 day probation during which his performance will be monitored closely.

column168: While consolidating hazardous waste onto a van trailer located at the Veolia ten-day in transit facility in Menomonee Falls, WI, a Veolia employee observed a small leak. Upon further investigation, the source of the spill was determined to be a 30 gallon metal drum of halogenated solvents. The leak was observed to be coming from two pin holes on the side of the drum. The holes may have been caused by the use of a drum grabber attachment on a forklift. Veolia employees contained the spill and placed the leaking drum into a salvage drum. The absorbents, used personal protective equipment, and spill clean-up debris also were placed into the salvage drum.
column169: This incident was reviewed with Veolia field personnel with an emphasis on ensuring that a thorough review of container integrity is performed prior to transporting a container of hazardous material. In addition, the proper use of the forklift drum grabber was reviewed with the ten-day in transit dock personnel.

column168: On September 11th, 2015, at 09:01 hours, personnel in the CSXT Buffalo Frontier Yard discovered CBTX 740385, a loaded UN 1267 of petroleum crude oil leaking from top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Great Northern Midstream, LLC was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-09-11-00083. EP+S of Vermont, the Buffalo Branch, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene, as well as CSXT Hazardous Material Systems Manager, Michael Bethge, during the investigation it was determined the liquid line valve was by-passing product, and the secondary securement TODO Quick Connect valve, by-passing product also, as the internal spring has weakened and oil is seeping by the dry-lock connection assembly.   With the issue identified, it was determined that the tank car would require a transload, as the package is not secure per 49 CFR 174.50, therefore corrective actions were taken to contain the release, these actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Dan Ruiz, Off: 713-800-7978.    NOTE: on the original waybill, dated 09/07/15, waybill Number 777-008569-780166, it reflected that Philadelphia Energy Solutions (PES) was the shipper of record, this was a computer error during entry on the part of Great Northern Midstream, LLC. It is so noted the Great Northern Midstream, LLC is taking full responsibility for this incident, and handling all recoverable costs associated with CBTX 740385 NAR incident.    Cause Code: 300 (2 points) and 310 (5 points)  NARRI: 2x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 40

column168: On September 16th, 2015 at 17:12 hours, personnel in the CSXT West Albany Yard discovered UTLX 201885, a loaded UN 1203, Aviation Gasoline tank car to have wetness down the sides of the tank car coming from the top fitting area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Flint Hills Resources, LP was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-09-16-00277. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont, the Glenmont branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was from the liquid line valve, the operating handle cross shaft packing gland, as product was bypassing the packing and dripping onto the tank car. EPSVT tightened the packing gland retainer nuts 1 turn each and the release was secured, UTLX 201855 was staged for 2 hours to verify no further release, the valve box cover was re-sealed and car was released.  Ms. Stacy Myers, office: was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. UTLX 201885 was released for transport and placement into Transflo Terminal Services.    Cause Code: 209 (5 points)  NARRI: 2x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

column168: It was reported that approximately 1 quart of UN2794 Battery acid released from a 398 lb battery that fell over during transit. The release impacted the trailer floor and the inside of the trailer. Terminal personnel up righted the battery and moved it off the trailer and it was reported that it was no longer leaking and had no visible damage. ERTS permitted terminal personnel to don PPE, over pack the damaged battery in a recovery drum, and neutralize the trailer floor with water and collect with absorbents. No waterways, soils, or storm drains were reported to have been impacted by this release.

column168: Our vehicle was traveling westbound on I-84 near Morgan, Utah early morning on 9-24-15 when it left the highway on the right shoulder causing both the lead and secondary trailers to overturn. The lead trailer did not experience any breach or loss of cargo; however, the secondary trailer received a large breach (approximately 8") on top near the front bulkhead. Emergency response teams were immediately involved and recovered all but 1000 gallons of product. It is believed that the majority of release took place immediately with some continuing for approximately 2 hours.
column169: The accident review/root cause process identified fatigue and speed as  major factors in this accident. As a result we have established defined policy requiring closer observance of daily speeds as provided by onboard recording devises. We have also instructed all dispatchers to pay closer attention to the driver schedules and do what is feasible to avoid day to day variances.

column168: A trailer hauling 12 (330) gal poly totes of UN3264 corrosive liquid was involved in a single vehicle rollover due to human error in Oak Ridge, LA on US 425 SB. There were no major injuries involved in this incident. The tractor trailer rolled on it's side causing damage to the 12 totes in the trailer and allowing approximately 400 gallons of product to release onto the soil and ditch line 10 ft away from the road. Hazmat contractors were dispatched to cleanup the release and remove the remaining product from the damaged totes.  Total waste generated was 2 roll offs of impacted soil and 3,000 gallons of product collected in a vac truck. No water was impacted by this release and the environment has been completely re mediated.

column168: General foreman reported above noted car leaking/venting at the plug at the liquid line valve. Car is located behind the Purina industry lead.    1800 CT from James Farner: Foreman will attempt to tighten the plug.    1910 CT from James Farner: Plug tightened and leak stopped. The problem is with a bypassing issue at the liquid line valve and further assessment and repairs will be needed. The car needs to be moved about 3/4 of a mile to free up the industry tracks for switching. Mr. Farner requested the SID to make state notification.    FRA-Gary Flores authorized movement verbally to nearest switch approximately 3/4 of mile to and from for an estimated total of 1.5 miles to spot the car on an industrial siding to minimize impact to industry leads.
column169: Shipper should review current SOP and forward the details of this incident to those in charge of loading and pre-trip inspections so they can review their procedures to prevent this from occurring in the future.

column25: Vitol by Kinder Morgan Liquids Terminals LLC
column162: ASST. DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: Comments from Inspection Report (9/17/15) by ODOT Hazmat Inspector (Chris Kuenzi):      "Description  Loose Manway Cover Swing Bolts: Inspection of this residue tank car marked UN1987 (Alcohols, NOS) found that two of six manway cover swing bolts were loose  and able to be moved by hand, causing it to be in non-conformance with the Hazardous Material Regulations. We noted an ethanol-like odor while on top of the car  and determined it was strongest near the manway, indicating that the loose manway cover was allowing product vapor to escape to the atmosphere.    49 CFR 173.31(d)(1)(iv) states that each person offering a tank car for transportation must perform an external visual inspection that includes determining that all  closures and all fastenings securing them are properly tightened in place by the use of a bar, wrench, or other suitable tool.    49 CFR 173.24(b)(1) states that, except as otherwise provided in this subchapter, there will be no identifiable (without the use of instruments) release of hazardous  materials to the environment."    A BNSF Hazmat Responder responded to secure the loose manway closure swing bolts.  BNSF was not able to confirm or identify a release occurring while securing the manway.  The reported amount released is an estimate only as ODOT was not able to provide additional details regarding the release.

Quick Fuel driver was fueling customer equipment from Company straight truck utilizing a hose and nozzle. The compartment on the straight truck he was fueling from ran dry during the process. The driver changed fueling compartments on the truck so he could continue fueling customer equipment. The driver left the fueling nozzle in the locked open position within the customer equipment fill pipe while changing fueling compartments on the truck. When the truck pump PTO initiated there was a surge of product within the fueling hose which caused the locked open nozzle to fall out of the customer equipment fill pipe causing a release on the impervious pavement.
column169: Driver is being retrained per Company policy that all dispensing nozzles will not be locked in the open position unless hands on and attended during any fueling operations.

column168: Approximately 35 minutes after the accident occurred (08:22), I was notified and was able to confirm the driver was uninjured. I was able to get a copy of the bill of lading for the truck from the office in Midland to see what cargo was onboard. Once our operations manager was onsite, he confirmed the product was leaking from the truck. At this point, Reagan county fire and our operations manager began laying down plastic sheeting, pigs and building dikes to stem product seepage. I initiated a call to Allied International Emergency, with whom we have a contract, to begin dispatch to the site. Allied arrived on scene at 12:45 to begin cleanup shortly thereafter, it was determined that 100 gallons of WS-415 had spilled; reportable quantity for this product is 53 gallons. I arrived in Midland and began notifications to NRC, TCEQ and the local LEPC at approximately 15:45. By 18:00, Allied had completed cleanup and remediation. It was determined that the driver fell asleep while driving and failed to negotiate a turn in the roadway. We have also determined that the valve on the tank had some corrosion.
column169: We currently have a STOP work policy in place. This has been reiterated with the emphasis out on self-awareness. We are a creating fatigue management policy and associated training. We are also implementing a more frequent inspection of the valves than what is called for in the Special Permit.

column168: At 1025 hours on 10 September 2015 CSX Transportation employees operating in the Willard, OH yard detected an odor emanating from Tank Car UTLX 213419 at MP BG 203.0. Initial reports indicated no obvious liquid or vapor release from the car, only an odor was detected. The CSX PSCC was notified, and Hazardous Materials Managers Joseph Taylor and Joseph Caccamo were notified. SUNPRO Environmental was dispatched from Canton, OH to respond and provide assistance.    Upon arrival SUNPRO was able to confirm the presence of the odor, as well as detectable levels of vapor with Photo Ionization within 1 meter of the car. It was determined the release point of the vapor was from a vacuum relief valve located in the top mounted protective housing, secured via 4 bolt flange to the pressure plate and nozzle. Initially, the vacuum relief valve was isolated with polypropylene sheeting to reduce the amount of detectable odor adjacent to the tank car, and allow for time to speak with the Shipper, Car Owner, Tank Car Builder, and Manufacturer of the identified valve.     It was determined that the parts required to stop the release, i.e. blind bolted flange or replacement valve would not be immediately available. Arrangements were made with Union Tank Car Mobile Repair Unit, in coordination with the Shipper to receive the necessary valve on 15 September 2015. The protective housing was double wrapped in polypropylene sheeting, and a deodorant was applied to contain the pungent detectable odor adjacent to the car. A monitoring team performed daily inspections of the tank car, and at 1500 hours on 15 September 2015 the defective vacuum relief valve was replaced in kind with identical Durlon 9000 gasket material. Upon replacement, no detectable odor or vapor was discovered by Photo Ionization.

column168: On September 27, 2015, at 10:38 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Avon Terminal, Avon, Indiana reported that an there was an odor from  UTLX 206682 , a residue tank car of UN1090, Acetone. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Nexeo Solutions, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2015-09-27-00021. Summit Contracting, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Avon Terminal. Summit found that two manway securement bolts were less than tool tight and the manway gasket was compressed and deteriorated. The shipper representative, MIKE BOMMARITO, was notified of the situation found. The manway gasket was replaced and the manway securement bolts were properly secured. column168: A trailer hauling UN1993 petroleum distillates in a 330 gal steel tote reported a small 3 oz release onto the top of the tote. The spill was due to the tote cap not being tightened properly for transport allowing for product to splash out during transit. Terminal personnel carefully cleaned up the release and tightened the cap. No water or soil was impacted by this release.

A BNSF unit ethanol train derailed seven loaded tank cars while operating on main track.  A fire ensued engulfing three of the derailed tank cars and all fires were extinguished by 1700 hrs.      Derailed tank car UTLX 206513 sustained a side tank puncture in the middle of the tank car.  Commodity remaining within UTLX 206513 was vacuumed out of UTLX 206513 and placed into portable frac tanks for future disposal.  UTLX 206513 deemed destroyed was cleaned and purged of hazardous material.    Derailed tank car SHPX 208456 sustained a head puncture at the A end. Commodity remaining within SHPX 208456 was vacuumed out of SHPX 208456 and placed into portable frac tanks for future disposal. SHPX 208456 deemed destroyed, was cleaned and purged of hazardous material.    Derailed tank car CBTX 716019 sustained bottom outlet valve damage allowing product to release from the ball valve. The spill was contained by natural barriers on site. Commodity remaining within CBTX 716019 was vacuumed out of CBTX 716019 and placed into receiving railcars for further shipment to end user. CBTX 716019 deemed destroyed, was cleaned and purged of hazardous material.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A terminal reported 8 (55) gal poly drums of a UN1866 resin solution which were leaking on the lids in the terminal due to the bungs not being tightened properly for transport. A contractor was dispatched to tighten the loose bungs and cleanup the 3 oz release. The drums were then staged in the OS&D pending shipper instructions. No soil or water was impacted y this release.

A Clean Harbors driver was loading a vaccuum tanker and during the process of loading, the driver cleared the hoses, closed both the internal & externl valves on the truck, and shut down the pump so that he could guage how much material was in the tanker.  When the driver open the dome to the tanker to measure, he noticed material leaking out the end of the hose.  The driver immediately turned on the vaccuum pump and vaccuumed up the material into the tanker that leaked out of the hose. The driver then wiped up any residual off the floor with absorbent pads and placed the pads in the appropriate container.
column169: The driver was retrained on the protocol of clearing hoses during a transfer.

column168: 1 gallon of UN2078 Lupranate T80 Type 2 Isocyanate released from an external valve on the tanker trailer. It was reported the elbow coming off the bottom of the tank was leaking. The valve only leaked when the tanker was put under pressure. The release impacted the asphalt lot.  Reichold personnel neutralized and then rinsed the solution into a drain leading directly to the waste water facility.  Contractors were dispatched to perform any more necessary clean up. The tanker was transported to a Trimac maintenance facility in St. Louis where a mechanic speculated that an internal valve was cracked.  Trimac dismissed the contractors and clean up activities were ended.

column168: R&L Carriers had a release of approximately 0.25 lbs of a solid UN3179 Sodium Nitrobenzonate,potassium cyanide in side trailer # SF1234 from a 5 lb fiber board pails. The release was found inside the trailer upon arrival. the cause of the release was a puncture. The release was cleaned up by a network contractor and placed in a 15 gallon drum for later disposal.

A Superior Carriers 407 tanker released approximately 15 gallons of UN1199 Furfurfal on to the asphalt at the roadside. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by the release. There were no road closures, no injuries, and no evacuations caused by the incident. Network contractors cleaned up the release thoroughly working absorbents into the asphalt to collect free standing liquid. The Contractor replaced a missing seal on the dome cap which was the cause of the release.

column168: There was a release of approximately 0.5 gallons of Un2922 Methylacrylate from a 55 gallon steel drum inside of trailer # 3118110 caused by a loose cap on the drum. The cap may have loosened during a temperature change. Network contractors clened up the release in the trailer thoroughly working absorbents into the triler floor to collect all liquid. One 55 gallon drum containing glycidyl methacrylate impacted absorbents and spent PPE was generated.

column168: At 0111 hours on September 25, 2015 BNSF Intermodal Hub manager in Portland, OR reported container SNLU 142227 was leaking an unknown substance onto outside of container and railcar DTTX 645365 which was transporting the container.  NRC Environmental was called by the shipper to investigate and remediate.  Upon arrival NRC gained access to the container with waybilled product of Paint, Class 3, PGII and found one drum which had leaked approximately one gallon of Valspar paint which had dried in place prior to their arrival.  The one 55 gallon drum was in a shipment of 61 others and was found to be the only one leaking from the seam at the bottom of the drum.  No impact/damage or other trauma to the drum was observed at the leak site.  Drum was placed in an overpack and the paint was cleaned from the interior and exterior of the container and railcar.  No paint touched the ground.
column169: Shipper should thoroughly inspect drums prior to loading to ensure no defects are present which could allow product to escape the container.

column168: TILX 101035 was observed leaking product from the liquid line valve flange on 9/12/15 at approximately 2205 hours. M&M Protection was notified to respond to the scene and stopped the leak at 2300 hours by venting the car to atmosphere. It was determined that the liquid line valve flange bolts were loose. The following morning 9/13 they attempted to tighten the bolts but could not get proper torque due to the narrow access to the bolts. On 9/14 they were able to get a crow foot wrench on the bolts and apply sufficient torque to secure the flange. The car was released and forwarded to destination, approximately 7 miles, for unloading. Per shipper, car is to be sent to a home shop to be examined and repaired as necessary.
column169: Shell Chemical responded immediately to the incident and is taking action to prevent future occurrence.

column168: ON 09/15/2015 A PACKAGE FIRE INCIDENT TOOK PLACE AT THE UPS- SYRACUSE, NY FACILITY AT 00:55 HRS. FIRE WAS OBSERVED ON A CONVEYOR BELT AT WHICH TIME A FULL EVACUATION WAS ORDERED AND ALL THE EMPLOYEES EXITED THE FACILITY. A MECHANIC RESPONDED TO THE AREA WITH ABC FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND EXTINGUISHED THE FLAME. THE FIRE WAS FROM PACKAGE WHICH IGNITED BY STATIC ELECTRICITY. FOUR OTHER PACKAGES WERE PARTIALLY BURNED. THE AREA WAS CLEANED UP AND THE ALL CLEAR WAS GIVEN TO EMPLOYEES TO ENTER THE FACILITY. THE EVACUATION LAST 15 MINUTES. NO FIRE DEPARTMENT OR POLICE WERE CONTACTED. NO INJURIED WERE REPORTED.
column169: NO RECOMMENDATIONS AT THIS TIME PENDING INVESTIGATION.

THE SORTER NOTIFIED THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR, ALICIA, & SHE CALLED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS.  WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  I PLACED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT OVER THE LIQUID ON THE FLOOR TO KEEP IT FROM SPREADING.  I THEN CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY.  I THEN PUT MORE CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT DOWN WHERE THE BOX HAD BEEN.  I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT & PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY.  I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 PLASTIC BOTTLE'S CAP HAD BECOME LOOSE & THAT ALL THE BOTTLES WERE SOILED BY THE PRODUCT

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON NORTH CAROLINA ROUTE #86 IN HILLSBOROUGH, NORTH CAROLINA. THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON STATE ROUTE 1545 AND FAILED TO STOP AT A STOP SIGN AND STRUCK THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE KENAN TRANSPORT,LLC TRACTOR.AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION, THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE UNIT AND IT WENT OFF THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED. THE TRACTOR WAS COMPLETELY CONSUMED BY FIRE AND THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS FATALLY INJURED. THE TRAILER CONTAINING 9400 GALLONS OF PROPANE WAS DAMAGED BUT THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASED. A LOCAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND ASSISTED KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC PERSONNEL IN TRANSFERRING THE PROPANE TO ANOTHER TRAILER. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.

column168: At 1140 hours on September 29, 2015, the conductor on the RLC304-28 noticed a foul smell coming from cars parked in Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) Rose Bluff yard.  KCS Environmental + Hazmat Department dispatched a response contractor to investigate.  The Louisiana State Police were notified and subsequently dispatched a Trooper.  Upon arriving, air monitoring was started.  SHPX 221521, a loaded Stabilized Butadiene tank car was found to be the source of the odor.  Upon opening the protective housing, the "B" end liquid valve DryLok connection was found to be frozen, indicating liquid butadiene was caught in the connection.  The shipper was notified and dispatched personnel to inspect and secure the tank car.  By the time the shipper arrived, the liquid valve had defrosted  so the pressure relief device mounted on the valve body was  removed to determine whether any liquid butadiene was caught in the valve. No liquid was found and the pressure relief device was replaced.     File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column14: POST RD AT OLD INDUSTRIAL PKWY
column168: A TANKER TRANSPORTING 7922 GALLONS OF DENATURED ETHANOL WAS TURNING AROUND A NEW ROUND ABOUT UNDER CONSTRUCTION AT THE INTERSECTION OF POST ROAD ONTO OLD INDUSTRIAL PARKWAY (NORTHBOUND) IN DUBLIN, OHIO, WHEN IT OVERTURNED. APPROXIMATELY 1,300 GALLONS OF DENATURED ETHANOL SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND AND INTO A STORM DRAIN CISTERN. THE REST OF THE PRODUCT WAS OFFLOADED. A PRIVATE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WORKED UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE OHIO EPA REPRESENTATIVE ONSITE. FIRE REGARDING FOAM AND SPILLED ETHANOL WAS VACUUMED AND CONTAINERIZED OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL. THE OHIO EPA SUPERVISED AEROSOLIZATION OF THE ETHANOL-WATER MIXTURE IN THE FIRE TANK AND CISTERN (THAT WAS ALREADY FILLED WITH WATER). THE FOAM IS BEING TRANSPORTED OFF SITE FOR DISPOSAL AND THE SITE WAS BACKFILLED AND RESTORED.
column169: HOC TRANSPORT HAS PROVIDED INSTRUCTIONS TO THEIR DRIVERS TO TAKE BETTER PRECAUTIONS WHEN HANDLING TANKERS, ESPECIALLY AROUND CORNERS.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING A TRUCK TRACTOR SEMI TRAILER (DROP DECK FLAT BED) WITH 13 IBC'S PURCHASED FROM THE MANUFACTURER IN NORMAN OK TO LINDSAY OK.  APPROXIMATELY 7 MILES NORTH OF LINDSAY THE DRIVER WAS SOUTH BOUND APPROACHING THE CREST OF A HILL WHEN ANOTHER TRUCK TRACTOR FROM THE NORTH BOUND LANE ENTERED INTO THE SOUTH BOUND LANE OF AN UNDIVIDED TWO LANE HIGHWAY.  TO AVOID A HEAD ON COLLISION THE DRIVER SWERVED ONTO THE UNIMPROVED SHOULDER AT WHICH TIME THE FORWARD MOST IBC ON THE PASSENGER SIDE SHIFTED LOOSE FROM ITS SECUREMENT AND SLID OFF THE FLAT BED SEMI TRAILER, HIT THE GROUND AND RUPTURED SPILLING ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.    THE IBC AND ALL MARKING/SPECIFICATION WERE DISPOSED OF BY THE REMEDIAL CLEAN-UP COMPANY PRIOR TO REPORT COMPLETION.

column168: THE SORTER AT DOOR 13 IN THE PRIMARY NOTICED THAT THE PACKAGE HE WAS ABOUT TO PULL OFF THE BELT APPEARED WET AND HAD HAZMAT MARKINGS SO HE STOPPED BELT & NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS OF THE LEAKING HAZMAT ON THE BELT. RUBEN, THE DMP SUPERVISOR, RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. HE UTILIZED HIS DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSES THE SITUATION. HE CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE TO A LINED SPILL TRAY. HE PLACED A SMALL AMOUNT OF CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT ON THE BELT TO ABSORB ANY LIQUID THAT MAY HAVE ESCAPED THE PACKAGE. HE SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT & ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. HE THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX TO PROCESS IT, I FOUND THAT 1 OF THE 4 BOTTLES WAS SLIGHTLY CRUSHED & HAIRLINE CRACK ALONG THE SIDE. 3 ADDITIONAL BOTTLES HAD SOILED LABELS & VISIBLE LIQUID ON THE BOTTOM.

column168: LIQUID WASTE IN THE DRUM CAUSED THE POLY DRUM TO BULGE AND FAILED AT THE WEAKEST POINT; CREATING A PINPOINT HOLE AT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLON LINE. THE LIQUID WASTE LEAKED TO A CORNER OF THE PARKED TRAILER SPILLING TO THE PAVEMENT IN THE TRUCK PARKING YARD. A DRIVER HEARD THE LIQUID SPILLING AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED STERICYCLE PERSONNEL WHO WERE ON SITE AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT.   THE STREAM OF LIQUID WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED BY PUTTING 2 X 20 GAL OVER PACK UNDER THE SMALL STREAM OF LIQUID AND PUTTING DRY ABSORBENT AND SPILL SOCKS ON AND AROUND THE SPILLED MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE SPREAD OF SPILLED LIQUID WASTE. WHEN THE WASTE STOPPED FLOWING, THE TRAILER WAS OFF LOADED UNTIL THE FAILED DRUM WAS IDENTIFIED. THE DRUM WAS PUT IN A 95 GALLON OVER PACK DRUM AND THE CAPTURED LIQUID WAS PUT IN A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM. THE TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PUT IN 3 SPILLS DEBRIS DRUMS TO BE MANIFESTED AND SHIPPED TO 21ST CENTURY ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT OF NEVADA FERNLEY DISPOSAL FACILITY.
column169: FOLLOW UP WITH GENERATOR TO ENSURE THE MATERIAL IS PACKAGED CORRECTLY AND COMPLIANT. FURTHER INVESTIGATION WITH DRUM SUPPLIER TO NOTE ANY ISSUES WITH POLY 55 DRUMS THAT MAY HAVE FAILED.     ACCORDING TO GENERATOR, THE DRUMS USING TO ACCUMULATE AND SHIP THIS WASTE WERE RECONDITION DRUMS. GENERATOR AGREES TO USE ONLY “NEW’ FOR THIS WASTE STREAM.

column168: THE PRODUCT IS OFF LOADED FROM A CARGO TANK TRAILER INTO A 2.5 MILLION GALLON HOLDING TANK THROUGH AN UNLET IN THE BOTTOM OF THE HOLDING TANK. APPARENTLY, THERE IS EITHER NO EXISTING BACKFLOW CHECK VALVE OR IF ONE EXIST IT DID NOT FUNCTION PROPERLY BECAUSE HEAD PRESSURE FROM THE HOLDING TANK WAS GREATER THAN THE TRAILER AND THE PRODUCT FROM THE HOLDING BACK FLOWED INTO THE CARGO TANK. ONCE THE CARGO TANK FILLED THE CARGO TANKS POP OFF VALVE OPENED (DO TO THE HIGH HEAD PRESSURE) AND PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF THE POP OFF VALUE. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE CARGO TANK'S VALUE AND STOPPED THE SPILLAGE.  UNKNOWN QUANTITY (BELIEVED TO BE LESS THAN 50 GALLONS) WAS SPILLED SOME OF IT ENTERED A STORM DRAW. ACCORDING TO PLANT FACILITY MANAGER KEVIN MILLER THE DRAIN LEADS TO THE MIAMI RIVER.

column168: A 275 GALLON IBC CONTAINING 265 GALLONS OF 2, 4-D AMINE HERBICIDE THAT HAD JUST BEEN LOADED ONTO A FLATBED DELIVERY TRUCK TO BE DELIVERED TO A CUSTOMER WAS PUNCTURE WITH ONE OF THE FORKS ON THE FORKLIFT DUE TO DRIVER ERROR. THE DRIVER WAS TRYING TO RE-POSITION THE IBC ON THE TRUCK SO HE COULD SECURE IT FOR TRANSPORT. THE CONTAINER WAS PUNCTURED LOW ON THE RIGHT SIDE AND APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS WAS SPILLED ON THE YARD AT HELENA CHEMICAL COMPANY IN TAFT, TX. THE RELEASE IS ESTIMATED TO HAVE LASTED 3-5 MINUTES, SINCE THE DRIVER WAS WORKING ALONE AND WAS UNABLE TO IMMEDIATELY RESPOND TO THE SPILL BEFORE MOST OF THE PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED THE IBC. THE SPILL IMPACTED AN AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 40 FEET BY 70 FEET.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE HELENA CHEMICAL COMPANY PROPERTY. THE INCIDENT WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO OUR CORPORATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE OFFICIAL WHO THEN REPORTED IT TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. OUR OUTSIDE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON SITE AFTER APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS TO START THE CLEAN UP PROCESS. AFFECTED SOIL AND GRAVEL WAS EXCAVATED AND PLACED IN ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS FOR STORAGE UNTIL DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THE EXCAVATION SITE WAS BACKFILLED WITH CLEAN REPLACEMENT MATERIAL.
column169: ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE SHIPPING AND HANDLING OF ALL MATERIALS HANDLED BY HELENA CHEMICAL COMPANY ARE TRAINED YEARLY ON FORKLIFT OPERATION AND SAFETY. EMPLOYEES ARE CONTINUALLY REMINDED ABOUT PROPER FORKLIFT OPERATION AND SAFETY. THE INCIDENT HAS SHOWN THAT ADDITIONAL FOLLOW-UP TRAINING IS NECESSARY AND IT SCHEDULED FOR THE NEXT ROUTINE SAFETY MEETING. WE HAVE ALSO IDENTIFIED THAT BESIDES ADDITIONAL TRAINING, IT IS HELPFUL TO HAVE A “SPOTTER” PRESENT TO HELP THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WHEN LOADING/UNLOADING TRUCKS.

column168: ON 9-10-15 AT 1130 HOURS CSDT, I WAS ADVISED OF A TANK CAR LEAKING AT THE INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) RAILROAD INDUSTRY TRACK IN BLUE ISLAND,IL. IHB TERMINAL SUPERINTENDENT STEVE DEUNN ADVISED CAR NUMBER NATX 300314, CONTAINING A FULL LOAD OF PTEROLEUM DISTILLATES UN 1268 PG 1 WAS DISCOVERED BY AN EMPLOYEE OF NUSTAR ENERGY. OPERATIONS CENTER PLACED THE MAIN LINE TRACKS LOCATED ADJACENT TO THE LEAKING TANK CAR ON STANDBY DUE TO FLAMMABILITY OF THE PRODUCT.    UPON ARRIVAL, MYSELF,  DAVE ESTEP AND CONOR SCHAFFER OF SUNPRO SERVICES INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID LINE INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON TOP OF THE CAR. PRODUCT WAS SPILLING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR AND DRIPPING ON TO THE RAIL BED APPROXIMATELY 2 DRIPS EVERY 4 SECONDS. AFTER USING A WRENCH TO TIGHTEN DOWN THE LIQUID LINE VALVE THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. AFTER REMEDIATION OF THE DISCHARGE PRODUCT WAS ACCOMPLISHED SUNPRO RPECEDED TO ALSO CLEAN THE OUTSIDE OF THE TANK CAR. THE TANK CAR WAS IN ROUTE TO NUSTAR ENERGY IN BLUE ISLAND, IL AND WAS SHIPPED FROM CENTENNIAL ENERGY IN RAYLAND, OH.    ON 9-11-15 MYSELF AND CONNOR SCHAFFER FROM SUNPRO BUBBLE TEST THE TANK CAR TO MAKE SURE THERE WERE NO MORE EXISTING LEAKS ANYWHERE ON THE TANK. THE BUBBLE TEST SHOWED THERE TO BE NO LEAKS AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO TRANSPORTATION.
column169: THERE NEEDS TO BE MORE THOROUGH INSPECTIONS OF TANK CARS BEFORE SENDING THEM OUT FOR TRANSPORTATION. HAVING A LIQUID LINE VALVE THAT WAS NOT EVEN TOOL TIGHT SHOWS EXTREME CARELESSNESS ON THE EMPLOYEE WHOS IGNED OFF ON THIS TANK CAR BEING READY FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: THE DRIVER OF TRACTOR 11944 AND TRAILER 6495 WAS IN ROUTE TO A CUSTOMER AND WAS TURNING LEFT OFF OF A BENDER ROAD ONTO COUNTRY CLUB ROAD. DURING THE PREPARATION TO UPRIGHT THE UNIT, MACON COUNTRY SHERRIFF GRANTED PERMISSION TO VENT THE PRODUCT THROUGH THE MANUAL VENT VALVE TO LIGHTEN THE LOAD FOR LIFTING. THE UNIT WAS UP RIGHTED AND WAS TOWED AWAY TO CLEAR THE SCENE.

column168: The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

At about 1:20 PM the driver connected all of the hoses, turned off the tractor and started loading through the spray fill as he had been instructed by the Airgas supervisor.  At approximately 1:50 the driver noticed that there was a spray of product coming from the top of the trailer and spraying approximately 10 feet in the air.   The driver radioed the control room to stop the pump.  They stopped the pump immediately. The driver estimated that approximately 10-15 gallons of material spilled from the top of the trailer before the flow was stopped. The driver closed all the valves and went to the control room to let the area air out for 25 minutes. The compression fitting on the vapor valve had come loose causing the material to spray from the compression fitting.  The compression fitting has been removed and the system has been hard piped to prevent failure in the future from over pressurization.

column168: DRIVER PARKED TO OFFLOAD GAS & DSL FUEL.  TRUCK EXPLODED WHICH RESULTED IN FIRE. THE PRODUCT BURNT UP AT THE TIME AND VAPORS
column169: BUMPER GUARDS INSTALLED SO TRUCKS CANNOT PULL WITHIN IS' TRUCKS. DURING TRAINING OF DRIVER, WE WILL BE REITERATING STRONGLY HOW IMPORTANT IT IS TO STAY MIN. 15' AWAY FROM ANY VENTS AND STAY.

column168: WHILE TRANSFERRING FUEL FROM OUR DELIVERY TRUCK, THE HOSE CLAP FAILED. THIS CAUSED THE HOSE TO POP OFF AND GAS BEING RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND. BY THE TIME OUR DRIVER WAS ABLE TO SHUT DOWN THE TRUCK AND STOP THE SPILL ABOUT 1 MINUTE HAD PASSED. THIS RESULTED IN 100 GALLONS OF GAS TO BE SPILLED ONTO THE CUSTOMERS PROPERTY. THE GAS WAS FLOWING DOWN TO THE ROAD. POLICE AND FIRE WERE CALLED. WITH THEIR HELP, WE WERE ABLE TO STOP THE SPILL FROM ENTERING AND DRAINS AND CLEAN IT UP. WE REPLACED ALL MATERIALS USED BACK TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE TANK WAS LOADED WITH 1279 GALLONS OF GAS AT THE TIME. OUR MECHANIC WAS CALLED TO SITE, AS WAS MYSELF, AND THE MECHANIC WAS ABLE TO FIX THE TRUCK LATER AT THE YARD. THE PROBLEM WAS FIXED BY REPLACING THE CLAMP WITH A NEW ONE.
column169: UNFORTUNATELY IT IS HARD TO PREVENT EQUIPMENT FAILURE, BUT WE DID HAVE A MEETING WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS. WE STRESSED TO THEM THE IMPORTANCE OF CHECKING THE EQUIPMENT AND MAKING SURE IT IS WORKING ORDER. WE ALSO TOLD THEM IF ANY PART SEEMS QUESTIONABLE DO NOT TAKE A CHANCE. WE ALSO HAD OUR MECHANIC CHECK ALL THE TOGETHER HOSE CLAMPS ON ALL OF OUR TRUCKS AND WILL BE SURE TO BE DOING THAT MORE OFTEN. WE WERE VERY GRATEFUL FOR THE QUICK RESPONSE FROM OUR WORKERS, POLICE, FIRE AND OTHERS INVOLVED. WE EMPHASIZED WE WERE VERY FORTUNATE THAT IS STAYED CONTAINED AND WERE ABLE TO CLEAN IT UP. WE POINTED OUT THE PROPER WAY TO RESPOND TO EMERGENCY SITUATION AND AREAS WE COULD HAVE IMPROVED. WE ALSO WENT OVER PUMPING PROCEDURES AND HOW TO BETTER AVOID ANOTHER INCIDENT.

column168: Incident Type: Spill w/ release to waterway  Date: September 9, 2015  Time: 1625 Hrs.  Location: West Haverstraw Marina, 600 Beach RD, W Haverstraw NY   Driver: William Givens  Vehicle: 821/4510  Weather: Clear and sunny – 83F  Injuries: None  Smoke/Fire/Private Property: None  Major Road Closure: None  Media: None  Incident Overview: Driver arrived at location to transfer diesel fuel from tank truck to above ground storage tank. Transfer was calculated without 10% safe overfill margin factored in. The driver who was in control of the transfer heard an audible change in the meter which calculates the amount transferred. This prompted the driver to cease transfer operations at which time he identified product spray from the vent pipe associated with the marina tank. Further investigation revealed that 10 gallons was discharged to the asphalt with < 3 gallons of over-spray from vent pipe to water.   Notifications:  • NRC: 1635 Hours – Report 1128012  • NYS DEC 1705 Hours – Report 1506141  Mitigation & Response: After the product transfer was terminated fuel was dispensed from the tank to a vehicle in order to reduce the fuel level within the tank. Drisol was used to contain product discharged to land and the marina provided boom to contain the over-spray in the water.  OSRO was dispatched at 1645 hours and arrived onsite at 1755 hours. Castleton Environmental will be conducting all remedial efforts and removing oil spill debris to an approved TSDF.   Investigation: Failed to determine if receiving tank can accept amount to be transferred in violation NYS environmental conservation law 613.3 resulting in release to the environment.   Disposition: In addition to violation of State law Mr. Givens also violated Company policy 0100-5 Loading & Delivery placing undue risk on the Company and causing harm to the environment based on his negligent actions. As such, Mr. Givens has been given a week suspension and is on all-inclusive final warning. column168: ELECTRO BATTERY-9-29-2015:    ON SEPTEMBER 29, 2015 AN ELECTRO EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING ON HIGHWAY 270 SOUTH, IN LANE 3, DRIVING APPROXIMATELY 56 MPH, WHEN A FIAT VEHICLE, IN LANE 4, WENT TO GET OFF THE HIGHWAY ONTO EXIT 40 EAST & WEST AND SUDDENLY CHANGED ITS COURSE. I DID NOT GET OFF AND DROVE LEFT INTO THE ELECTRO DRIVERS LANE AND CAME IN CONTACT WITH HIS RIGHT FRONT WHEEL.     WHEN THE CAR HIT THE RIGHT FRONT WHEEL OF THE TRUCK, THE CAR WAS DRAGGED APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET. WHEN THE CAR WAS RELEASE FROM THE TRUCK, THE TRUCK OVERTURNED ONTO THE DRIVER’S SIDE AND SLID APPROXIMATELY 150 FEET ON CONCRETE, HITTING 4 MORE VEHICLES.     ON THE SCENE WAS THE DOT, POLICE, AND FIRE COMPANY. THE TOW COMPANY WAS GOING TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP AND ASKED IF ELECTRO BATTERY HAD ANY POINTERS ON THE PROPER CLEAN UP. ELECTRO EMPLOYEES SUGGESTED THAT THEY HAD SODA ASH AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS BACK AT THE WAREHOUSE AND WOULD GLADLY GO GET THEM AND ASSIST IN THE CLEAN-UP. THIS WAS TALKED OVER WITH THE FIRE/FIRST RESPONDERS AND THEY ALL AGREED. ONCE THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS ARRIVED THERE WERE 4 ELECTRO EMPLOYEES HELPING TO CLEAN UP THE INCIDENT. THEY WENT THROUGH THE BATTERIES AND SORTED THEM AND RE-PALLETIZED THEM. BATTERIES THAT WERE CRACKED AND LEAKING WERE BAGGED AND PUT ON A SEPARATE PALLET AS PER EAST PENN’S/ PHMSA’S PROTOCOL ON DAMAGED BATTERIES. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT 25 BATTERIES WERE BAGGED. ONCE THE BATTERIES WERE RE-PALLETIZED AND SHRINK WRAPPED THEY WERE LOADED ONTO ANOTHER ELECTRO TRUCK. ONCE THE BATTERIES WERE LOADED THEY STARTED TREATING THE ACID THAT WAS SPILLED ON THE ROAD AND IN THE INSIDE OF THE ROLL-OVER TRUCK WITH SODA ASH. THE FIRST RESPONDERS INSTRUCTED THE ELECTRO EMPLOYEES TO TREAT ANY WET SPOTS WITH SODA ASH. APPROXIMATELY 14-50 LB BAGS OF SODA ASH WERE USED FOR THE CLEAN-UP. ONCE THE SODA ASH WAS DOWN AND NEUTRALIZED THE WET SPOTS, THE FIRE CO/FIRST RESPONDERS HOSED DOWN THE AREA.     THE BATTERIES WERE TAKEN BACK TO THE ELECTRO WAREHOUSE TO GO THROUGH TO ASSESS THE DAMAGE. BATTERIES THAT DID NOT MEET THE EAST PENN/ELECTO STANDARDS WERE RETURNED BACK TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO., IN LYON STATION, PA FOR RECLAMATION AT OUR SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER.
column169: NO ACTIONS TAKEN DUE TO AN ACCIDENT CAUSED BY ANOTHER VEHICLE.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 19, 2015, AIR LIQUIDE DRIVER FINISHED LOADING LIQUID OXYGEN INTO HIS TRAILER BUT WAS STILL CONNECTED TO THE LOAD LINE, WHEN HE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM AIR LIQUIDE’S NATIONAL SCHEDULING CENTER. THE LOGISTICS ANALYST INFORMED THE DRIVER HIS DELIVERY SCHEDULE HAD CHANGED, AND HE WOULD NEED TO RETRIEVE THE ADDITIONAL PAPERWORK FROM THE CONTROL ROOM. THE DRIVER WENT INTO THE CONTROL ROOM TO GET HIS ADDITIONAL PAPERWORK, AND DECIDED TO MAKE CORRECTIONS TO THE DELIVERY MANIFEST WHILE THERE. ONCE HE COMPLETED THE TASK HE RETURNED TO HIS TRACTOR AND PROCEEDED TO TAKE HIS MANDATORY 30 MINUTE LUNCH BREAK. THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO PULL AWAY FROM THE LOADING AREA, FORGETTING HE WAS STILL CONNECTED TO THE LOAD LINE. HE FELT RESISTANCE AND STOPPED THE VEHICLE IMMEDIATELY. THE DRIVER EXITED THE CAB OF THE VEHICLE AND REALIZED THAT HE WAS STILL CONNECTED TO THE LIQUID LOAD LINE AND HAD CAUSED THE LOAD LINE HOSE TO BREAK AND LIQUID O2 WAS SPILLED FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE SCALE AND SURROUNDING AREA. THE TRAILER WAS WEIGHT CAPACITY IN LIQUID, APPROXIMATELY 4500 GALLONS OF WHICH APPROXIMATELY 4000 GAL OF O2 WAS SPILLED UPON THE GROUND AND VAPORIZED.
column169: AIR LIQUIDE WILL CONTINUE TRAINING TO THE PRINCIPLES OF THE SAFE START SYSTEM-"EYES ON TASK/MIND ON TASK" AS PART OF ITS DRIVER SAFETY TRAINING. column168: ON SEPTEMBER 27, 2015, A AIR LIQUIDE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON POLK PARKWAY WITH A LIQUID EMPTY (RESIDUE) C02 TRAILER. HE NOTICED CO2 WAS VENTING THROUGH THE TRAILER VENT STACK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED SAFELY ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD, THEN PROCEEDED TO CHOCK HIS TRACTOR AND SET OUT THE EMERGENCY TRIANGLES. THE DRIVER THEN OPENED THE DOORS ON THE TRAILER TO CHECK THE INTERNAL TANK PRESSURE, WHICH READ 150 PSIG. THE DRIVER ALSO NOTICED THE MAIN SAFETY HAD LIFTED. THE FLORIDA HIGHWAY PATROL (FHP) WAS IN THE VICINITY AND STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE. UPON EVALUATION, THE FHP OFFICER DECIDED TO CALL THE POLK COUNTY SPECIAL OPS FIRE DEPARTMENT. IT WAS THEN DETERMINED BY THE POLK COUNTY SPECIAL OPS FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ESCORT THE EQUIPMENT TO A SAFE HAVEN AND ALLOW THE TRAILER TO CONTINUE VENTING UNTIL 0 PRESSURE WAS OBTAINED. ONCE REACHING 0 PRESSURE, THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED AND THEN RETURNED BACK TO THE DEPOT FOR ASSESSMENT. THE TRAILER WAS LIQUID EMPTY (RESIDUE) AND APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS WAS VENTED AND VAPORIZED.
column169: AIR LIQUIDE WILL CONTINUE TO FOLLOW OUR CURRENT PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE (PM) PROCEDURES REGARDING THE MAINTENANCE AND REPLACEMENT SCHEDULE FOR THE SAFETIES ON OUR CO2 TRAILERS. ONCE THE TRAILER HAS BEEN INSPECTED AND A DETERMINATION HAS BEEN MADE WHAT CAUSED THE FAILURE, REPAIRS WILL BE MADE. AIR LIQUIDE WILL CONTINUE TO MONITOR THE INDUSTRY FOR PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE, REPLACEMENT SCHEDULES. WE WILL WORK CLOSELY WITH OUR VENDORS ON RECOMMENDATIONS REGARDING UPGRADES IN VALVE TECHNOLOGY. WE WILL MAKE THE APPROPRIATE UPDATES TO OUR TRAINING, PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE AND REPLACEMENT SCHEDULES.

column168: Driver was loading APR truck #16-47 from tanks in our owned facility. He miscalculated and overloaded acompartment and saw it oozing out so he opened vapor line and the pressure of it sprayed out and spilledeverywhere. He was pushed back by pressure and covered in diesel. He had showered inside and left property to goget cleaned up more. Operations manager estimated that based on compartment size and what was pumped, about222 gallons spilled, but probably about 20 stayed on top of truck and another 25+ on ground, so less than 200 gallonsinto catch basin that leads to oil-water-separator. When I arrived onsite our operations manager and another driverhad already done quite a bit of clean-up on top of truck and on concrete pad. Call to WA EMD regarding spill since itwas in catch basin. He would notify Ecology. WA EMA Incident report #15-3620. Around 8:54pm received call backfrom Eric at NRC (clean-up supervisor), said he was getting crew together and would head down. Around 9:00pm callto National Response Center, they took report and relayed to various agencies. NRC Incident report #1127838. Wesurveyed our stormwater treatment system down stream in the catch basin system and there were no impacts, allfuel had remained contained in OWS that is just down from impacted catch basin. Around 9:12pm received call fromEPA regarding spill report they received from NRC, provided details and they were satisfied that everything wasunder control. Around 9:18pm received call from Doug Stoltz with Ecology, explained details and he was satisfied thateverything was under control also. Around 9:21 pm received call from Coast Guard, explained no waterway impacted,they were satisfied. Around 10:05pm NRC clean-up supervisor arrived, I showed him impacted areas. Productcontained to first catch basin on tank pad and oil-water-separator near tank pad, nothing appeared to go farther thanthat. We wiped down truck and put more pads down and had our dispather move the truck.Around 11:15pm the rest of the NRC clean-up crew arrived and worked to get property, catch basin and OWScleaned up. City of Tacoma inspected on 9/8/15 and were satisfied with clean-up.
column169: IT WAS DISOVERED THROUG THIS ICIDENT THAT THE OVERFILL PREVENTION SYSTEM INSTALLED AT OUR LADING RACK WAS NOT OPERATIONAL. THIS SYSTEM IS DEIGNED TO SHUT OFF MOTORS THAT PUMP INTO THE TRUCK ONCE THE COMPARTMENT LEVEL REACHES A SENSOR. IMMEDIATLEY FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT WE HAD A SEVRICE PROVIDER VIST OUR SITE TO DETERMINE WHAT PARTS AND REPAIRS WE NEED TO THIS SYSTEM TO MAKE IT OPERATIONAL. IF OPERATING CORRECTLY WITH CORDS HOOKED UP, THERE WOULD BE NO CHANCE OF AN OVERFILL INTO A TRUCK WHILE LOADING. THIS SYSTEM WAS REPAIRED AND MADE OPERATIONAL ON 11/25/2015 AND IS NOW IN USE FOR ALL LOADING OPERATIONS AT THIS LOAD RACK

column168: BRT TRACTOR TRAILER (BULK FUEL TANKER) WAS TRAVELING I-95SB IN LEFT CENTER LANE OF FOUR SOUTHBOUND LANES. THE VEHICLE IN THE FAR RIGHT SOUTHBOUND LANE ATTEMPTED TO MOVE LEFT INTO RIGHT CANCER LANE AND FORCED A VEHICLE IN THAT LANE INTO THE BRT TANKER. A FOURTH VEHICLE WAS ALSO INVOLVED IN THE COLLISION (DETAILS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME). THE IMPACT OF THE COLLISION TORE OFF ONE OF THE LOADING HEADS ON THE TANKER. RACE GAS SPILLED FROM THE DAMAGED UNIT. BRT DRIVER TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO CONTAIN THE SPILL, USING SPILL PADS AND A SNAKE TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM ENTERING A NEARBY STORM DRAIN. A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT MAY HAVE ENTERED THE STORM DRAIN. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREWS ARRIVED AND PLACED A CONTAINMENT POOL UNDER THE DAMAGED UNIT TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE FROM REACHING THE GROUND/PAVEMENT. BRT BROUGHT IN ANOTHER TANKER UNIT TO PUMP THE REMAINING PRODUCT OFF THE LEAKING TRAILER. BOTH TRAILERS WERE THEN DRIVEN FROM THE DAMAGED TRAILER. VEEDER ROOT READING INDICATED 7,811 GALLONS ON THIS DELIVERY. TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS OF SPILL WASTE (SPILL PADS, OIL DRY) WERE SWEPT UP AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT. WE ESTIMATE THAT THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 189 GALLONS; HOWEVER, MOST OF THIS PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AS THE LEAKAGE OCCURRED. OUR ESTIMATE OF PRODUCT THAT ACTUALLY REACHED THE GROUND/PAVEMENT IS 30 GALLONS. EMERGENCY RESPONSE INCLUDED BELVEDERE FIRE CO., MINISQUA FIRE CO., DE STATE POLICE, AMBULANCES, DNREC, HYDROCHEM, AND DELDOT TRAFFIC CONTROL.  SEE ATTACHED REPORTS AND PHOTOS.

column168: While unloading at the destination point, our hose came disconnected from the customers pump, which was pumping into an above ground tank. Upon discovery of the hose disconnection the driver shut the safety valves on our tank and shut the customers pump off. He contained the spilled ULSD with oil pads and booms. After the oil was contained and cleaned he unloaded the remainder of the load safely. After unloading the rest of the product it was determined that approximately 70 gallons had been released. All 3 owners of the company were at the facility within 45 minutes of the call from the driver to evaluate the situation. We cleaned the oil with pads, booms and oil dry. J & J spill company was also notified to assist with the cleanup operation and disposed of all contaminated product. After careful evaluation of the incident we determined it was driver error and could have been prevented by assuring the hose was attached property. Our decision was to terminate the employee
column169: We have an ongoing safety training program in place which is continuously monitored by our safety director. We hold monthly safety meetings and due to this incident we used it as a focal point for our October meeting. We discussed why this accident may have occured and how to prevent it in the future. As a group, including owners, managers and drivers, we concluded 3 main points that could have prevented this occurrence: 1. Always double checking hose connections before loading/unloading  2. Using velcro straps around the cam locks to assure the hose stays attached when pumping, especially with the pressures that are present during a pump off  3. Always checking equipment for worn or broken cam locks, hose ends, or damaged clamps, and getting them repaired/replaced. The hose in this incident was in good condition, and the driver had velcro straps in his truck, which he failed to use, therefore we do feel this incident was driver error which is why we decided to terminate the employee. Part of the October safety meeting included the drivers & managers personally going out in the yard and checking every hose and fitting to assure they have the proper equipment and it is in good condition. It was made clear that these procedures are to be done during their daily pre/post trip vehicle inspections

column168: WHILE STOPPED AT THE LOVE'S TRUCK STOP IN JASPER AL FOR A REST BREAK THE TRANSPORT DRIVERS WERE CONDUCTING AN EN ROUTE INSPECTION OF THE TRACTOR/ TRAILER INCLUDING THE PORTABLE TANK. THE DRIVERS FOUND A SLOW BUT STEADY LIQUID DRIP COMING FROM AROUND THE PORTABLE TANK OUTLET VALVE AREA. THEY IMMEDIATELY PLACE A CONTAINMENT BUCKET IN PLACE TO CATCH THE MATERIAL AND REPORTED THE SUSPECTED LEAK TO MILLER MANAGEMENT. A SUITABLE CARGO TANK FOR THE MATERIAL WAS LOCATED AND DISPATCHED TO JASPER AL. USES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE RESPONDED FROM BIRMINGHAM AL AND THE MILLER ER RESPONSE TEAM FROM MEMPHIS, TN RESPONDED. THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE SUSPECTED LEAKING TANK INTO A CARGO TANK TRAILER.     THE PORTABLE TANK WAS RETURNED TO THE EXPORT FREIGHT HANDLER. VOPAK IN SAVANNAH GA. THE TANK WAS CLEANED INSPECTED AND TESTED. NO DEFECTS OR LEAKS WERE IDENTIFIED. IT IS THEIR OPINION THE ALLEGED LEAK MUST HAVE BEEN RAIN WATER WHICH FOUND ITS WAY UNDER THE SKIN AND INSULATION AND WAS EXITING THE OUTER PROTECTIVE SKIN NEAR THE OUTLET VALVE AREA. IT WAS NOT RAINING AT THE TIME THE ALLEGE LEAK WAS FOUND BUT THE TANK HAND BEEN IN RAIN EARLIER.     MILLER BELIEVES A GASKET LEAKED AT THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE FOOT VALVE AND THE BOTTOM OF THE PORTABLE TANK BUT AS STATED ABOVE NO SUCH LEAK COULD BE DUPLICATED AFTER THE PORTABLE TANK AND HAS BEEN CLEANED OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: A CYTEC EMPLOYEE DRIVING A RENTED PICK-UP TRUCK WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 77 SOUTH DURING HEAVY RAIN WHEN THEY LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE TRAVELING OFF THE HIGHWAY, THROUGH THE MEDIAN AND INTO THE SOUTH BOUND LANES. THE PICKUP TRUCK RAN HEAD ON INTO A FLATBED TRACTOR TRAILER. THE PICK-UP SPUN 360 DEGREES AND CAME TO REST IN THE LEFT LANE WHERE IT CAUGHT FIRE. THE FLATBED RAN OFF THE HIGHWAY, THROUGH A BARBED WIRE FENCE AND ENDED UP IN A PASTURE. THE DRIVER OF THE PICK-UP TRUCK WAS PULLED OUT OF THE VEHICLE AND WAS DRIVEN BY AMBULANCE TO SAN ANTONIO MILITARY MEDICAL CENTER IN SERIOUS CONDITION. THE WEATHER WOULD NOT PERMIT A HELICOPTER FLIGHT. THE FLAT BED DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO CITIZENS MEDICAL CENTER IN STABLE CONDITION.     THE PICK-UP WAS CARRYING 5 GALLON DG CONTAINERS OF WEAK SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION TO BE DELIVERED TO DGM FOR SHIPMENT TO CYTEC’S R&D LABS IN STAMFORD, CT FOR INTERNAL USE AND EVALUATION. TWO OF THE SIX CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF SOLUTIONS. TONY HUFFMAN (CYTEC SHE) WAS NOTIFIED AND HE INITIATED NOTIFICATION OUR CLEANUP CONTRACTOR; SET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. OTHER NOTIFICATIONS WERE DONE AS WELL SUCH AS CHEMTREC, TCEQ AND FIRE RESPONSE. ERIM RESPONSE WAS INITIATED USING SET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED FOR SEVERAL HOURS UNTIL CLEAN-UP AND INVESTIGATION WAS COMPLETE.
column169: 1. DEFENSIVE DRIVING FOR THE FIELD TECHNICAL STAFF.   2. ANNUAL REFRESHER AWARENESS DOT TRAINING FOR TECHNICAL CUSTOMER SUPPORT STAFF.   3. AWARENESS TRAINING ON DOT REGULATIONS FOR TRANSPORTING AND SHIPPING OF HAZARDOUS AND DG SAMPLES.   4. CYTEC POLICY REFRESHER ON HAZMAT’ PROTOCOLS FOR PERSONNEL VEHICLES, EMPLOYEES AND STORAGE.   5. USE COMMERCIAL CARRIER UNDER CYTEC CONTRACT WHENEVER POSSIBLE.   6. ENSURE THAT CONTAINERS ARE ADEQUATELY SECURE IN VEHICLE PRIOR TO TRANSPORT.   7. CYTEC BUSINESS UNIT OR CYTEC’S LOGISTIC MANAGER TO WORK WITH CUSTOMERS FOR DG/DOT/SHIPMENTS.  8. HAVE AN INTERNAL LEAD WHO MAINTAINS CERTIFICATION/QUALIFICATION FOR TRANSPORTING AND SHIPPING OF HAZARDOUS AND DG MATERIALS.

column168: THE PTL TRUCK STOPPED AT THE WEIGH STATION FOR ROUTINE INSPECTION AND WEIGHT. THE TRAILER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING BATTERY ACID AND WAS PARKED. THE DRIVER CALLED PTL AND REPORTED THE LEAKAGE. MS. MCCUISTON OF PASCHALL TRUCK LINES (PLT_ CONTRACTED MR. DENNIS MELTON OF REQUESTED A RESPONSE TEAM TO REMEDIATE THE RELEASE. MR. MELTON CALLED A LOCAL SUBCONTRACTOR AND DISPATCHED A CREW TO THE SITE. THE CREW FOUND SEVERAL LARGE BATTERIES HAD BROKEN THEIR PALLETS AND WERE LAYING ON THEIR SIDE AND ALSO ON TOP OF SMALLER BATTERIES CAUSING SPILLAGE OF ACID FROM SEVERAL BATTERIES. IT APPEARED THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED FORWARD DURING HARD BRAKING OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER. THE CREW RELOCATED THE FREIGHT INSIDE THE TRAILER TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE DAMAGED BATTERIES. THE BATTERIES WERE INDIVIDUALLY INSPECTED AND IF SOUND TO BE LEAKING OR CRACKED, THEY WERE PLACED INTO POLY DRUMS. THE BATTERIES FOUND TO BE UNDAMAGED WERE DECONTAMINATED AND SET ASIDE FOR RELOADING. AFTER THE BATTERIES WERE MOVED, THE CREW USED CLAY ABSORBENT, ACID PADS AND HYDRATED LIME TO DECONTAMINATE THE TRAILER FLOOR, THE EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND THE AREA UNDER THE TRAILER. THE IMPACTED AREAS UNDER THE TRAILER MEASURED APPROXIMATELY 2 FEET BY 2 FEET AND 2 INCHES BY 8 FEET. UNDAMAGED BATTERIES WERE RELOADED AND SECURED. SIX 66 GLASS POLY DRUMS CONTAINING THE DAMAGED BATTERIES AND THE CLEANUP DEBRIS WERE LABELED AND LEFT IN THE TRAILER. CAUSE OF INCIDENT: HARD BRAKING CASED THE LOAD TO SHIFT AND DAMAGE TO THE FREIGHT.

column168: AT APPROX 5:45 AM ON 09/17/15, SUPERVISOR ED SMALL WAS NOTIFIED THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PKG IN TRAILER #370930. column168: ON SEPTEMBER 16, 2015, AN EAST PENN LOGISTICS DRIVER WAS HEADED WESTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 10 HEADING TO HOUSTON, TX TO DELIVER INDUSTRIAL BATTERIES. AT APPROXIMATELY 0430, THE DRIVER APPROACHED ROSE CITY, TX A SMALL TOWN APPROXIMATELY 15 MILES WEST OF THE FLYING J TRUCK STOP. AS HE CONTINUED TO TRAVEL WESTBOUND, HE WAS LOOKING DOWN TO PUT ON EMPTY SODA BOTTLE INSIDE A TRASH BAG HE KEPT IN HIS CAB. WHEN HE LOOKED UP, HE SAW TRAFFIC HAD STOPPED. THE DRIVER COULD NOT STOP IN TIME AND HE COLLIDED WITH 2 OTHER VEHICLES THAT WERE STOPPED IN FRONT OF HIM.     THE LOCAL POLICE WERE ON SCENE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT CLEANED UP THE DEBRIS AT THE SCENE. IT WAS UNCLEAR IF THE ROAD WAS CLOSED. THE LOAD DID SHIFT, AND ONE BATTERY FELL, BUT WAS STABLE ENOUGH TO BE TOWED TO A LOCAL TOW YARD. THERE WAS NOTHING LEAKING OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE TOWING FACILITY CALLED A LOCAL CLEAN-UP COMPANY FOR THE CLEAN-UP OF THE TRAILER. THE BATTERIES WERE ALL REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH ASH AND RINSED BY THE CONTRACTOR. ALL BATTERIES THAT WERE UNSTABLE WERE RE-PALLETIZED AND STRAPPED. THE BATTERY THAT FELL WAS UP-RIGHTED, RE-PALLETIZED AND STRAPPED. ONCE THE TRAILER WAS CLEAN, THE BATTERIES WERE LOADED BACK ON THE TRAILER. THE LOAD WAS RETURNED TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING, CO., LYON STATION PA, FOR ANALYSIS OF THE BATTERIES TO DETERMINE IF THEY WOULD BE SCRAP OR NEEDED REPAIR TO BE SOLD AS PRODUCT. NO BATTERIES WERE SCRAPPED. SOME DID NEED REPAIR FOR RESALE.     THE TRAILER AND THE TRUCK WERE INSPECTED BY THE INSURANCE COMPANY. THE TRAILER WAS FINE, NO DAMAGE AND IS BACK IN USE. THE TRUCK WILL NEED REPAIR BEFORE BACK IN USE.
column169: THE EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO. ACCIDENT REVIEW COMMITTEE REVIEWS ALL ACCIDENTS WHERE THE DAMAGED VALUE IS $1500 OR GREATER. IF THE ACCIDENT IS DEEMED PREVENTABLE BY THE COMMITTEE, THE DRIVER WOULD RECEIVE A DRIVER’S CODE OF CONDUCT VIOLATION. IF A TREND OF LIKE INCIDENTS THEN INVESTIGATING AND RETRAINING WILL OCCUR.

column168: AN AIR LIQUIDE RAIL CAR WAS TRAVELING FROM PLAQUEMINE LA TO SANTA FE SPRINGS, CA ON THE UNION PACIFIC RAIL LINE. AS THE RAIL CAR WAS TRAVELING OUTSIDE OF LA COSTE, TX, THE UNION PACIFIC CREW OBSERVED UNUSUAL VENTING FROM RAIL CAR INPX1-81, WHICH IS OPERATED BY AIR LIQUIDE. UNION PACIFIC’S HAZMAT SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED CHEMTREC IN REGARDS TO THE UNUSUAL VENTING OF THE CAR AND REQUESTED SOMEONE FROM AIR LIQUIDE CONTACT HIM. THE DIRECTOR OF SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY CHEMTREC AND REACHED OUT TO THE UP SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR INDICATED HIS TEAM WAS AWARE OF THE NORMAL VENTING PROCESS OF A RAIL CAR, BUT THIS VENTING LOOKED UNUSUAL AND HE WAS A CONTRACT CREW TO RESPOND TO THE VENTING RAIL CAR. THE AL DIRECTOR OF SAFETY CONTACTED THE NATIONAL SUPPLY MANAGER REGARDING THE EVENT AND HE CONTACTED HIS RAIL CAR MECHANIC TO OFFER SUPPORT FOR THE SITUATION.       THE AIR LIQUIDE RAIL CAR MECHANIC CONTACTED THE CONTRACT CREW, TO OFFER ASSISTANCE IN DETERMINING THE VENTING ISSUE. THE CONTACT CREW AND MECHANIC TRIED VARIOUS ITEMS TO DETERMINE THE ISSUE AND RESOLVED THAT THERE WAS VACUUM ISSUE AS WELL AS A CRACK IN THE VAPORIZER WHICH WAS CAUSING THE ABNORMAL VENTING. THE CONTRACT CREW REDUCED THE INTERNAL PRESSURE OF THE TANK CAR, WHICH ENABLED IT TO CONTINUE TO ITS DESTINATION WHERE IT WAS OFF LOADED. THE TANK CAR WAS THEN SENT TO THE MANUFACTURE FOR A DIAGNOSTIC REVIEW AND EVALUATION.
column169: REGARDING THE RECOMMENDATIONS OR ACTIONS TO BE TAKEN TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS EVENT, AIR LIQUID WILL CONTINUE TO FOLLOW ITS ESTABLISHED PROCESSES AND PROCEDURES IN REGARDS TO THE LOADING AND SHIPPING OF ARGON LIQUID. WE WILL MAKE MODIFICATIONS TO THOSE PROCESSES, OUR TRAINING OF PERSONNEL AND THE HANDLING OF THE PRODUCT AS THE REGULATORY CHANGES REGULATE. AIR LIQUIDE WILL CONTINUE TO FOLLOW THE REQUIRED INSPECTIONS, TESTING OF ITS RAIL CARS AND MAKE NEEDED REPAIRS AND IMPROVEMENTS WHEN NEEDED. ONCE THE DIAGNOSTICS OF THE RAILCAR IS COMPLETED, ANY CHANGES OR REPAIRS WHICH HAVE BEEN EVALUATED BY THE MANUFACTURER WILL BE MADE.

column168: During unloading, the CTMV driver moved the line and the line uncoupled, spraying the driver. The driver then walked away to rinse the material off. The driver was not able to close the valves to mitigate the release due to injuries sustained from the hazardous material. All remaining material was drained out of the CTMV through the uncoupled unloading line. Subsequent investigation revealed that the coupling was not defective, and that the driver did not fully tighten the coupling prior to unloading the hazardous material.   QC# E47886

The employee was unhooking the liquid withdrawal line and  was taking a valve off and turned it too far and the propane sprayed on the employee wrist. The employee was able to tighten the valve up and stop the leak very quickly but by that time the employee already had blisters. There was about one gallon of liquid propane released before the employee had it under control. The employee was treated at the emergency room they dressed the wound applied cream and he was discharged. No lost time from work it was just a surface burn. The employee is to follow up on 09/30/15 to make sure it is healing with no issues.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED SHIPMENT WAS FIRST NOTICED BECAUSE THE OUTER PACKAGE HAD BROKEN OPEN AT THE RAMP. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOX CONTAINED DRY ICE, BUT HAD NEVER BEEN INSPECTED AT ORIGIN. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND I CONTACTED DAVE KING OF THE SEA / FAA AT 10:30 ON 9-4-2015 TO ADVISE OF THE INCIDENT. PHOTOS WERE TAKEN AND I PROVIDED TO MR. KING. UPON DISCUSSION WITH HIM, I TOLD HIM THIS WAS A SHIPMENT GOING TO A GROUP OF MEN THAT WERE LEAVING IN THE AM ON HORSEBACK AND THEY WOULD NOT BE BACK FOR ABOUT A WEEK AND THERE WERE PROVISIONS IN THE PACKAGE THAT WOULD GO BAD IF NOT MOVED ON. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN LABELED, MARKED AND PREPARED AND IT WAS RELEASED TO MOVE ON TO THE DESTINATION BY FEEDER AIRCRAFT THE NEXT DAY. THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED THE FOLLOWING AM.

CLAIMANT VEHICLE #1 MADE AN IMPROPER LANE CHANGE AND STRUCK THE SIDE OF CLAIMANT VEHICLE #2. CLAIMANT VEHICLE #2 LOST CONTROL AND STRUCK THE LEFT SIDE OF THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC TRAILER. AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION, THE TRAILER WAS COMPROMISED AND LOST APPROXIMATELY 3200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. THE GASOLINE WAS ABLE TO IMPACT A NEARBY STORM DRAIN. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND IS HANDLING THE REMEDIATION WHICH IS ONGOING AS OF THIS DATE.

column168: ON 09/30/2015 AT 7:40 A PACKAGE WAS MOVED TO THE CLERK FOR REPACKING AS THE PACKAGE WAS WET FROM THE RAIN EXPOSURE. UPON REMOVING THE OUTER PACKAGING, THE CLERK DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER PACKAGE (WOODED CRATE) HAD TRIGGER TERMS PRINTED ON CRATE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS MEETS THE CRITERIA OF AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT SHIPMENT. THE UPS HAZMAT HELPDESK WAS CONTACTED AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AS A SECURITY HOLD PENDING FURTHER INVESTIGATION. ON 10/1/15 THE FACILITY SECURITY DEPARTMENT CONTACTED THE NY STATE POLICE TO HELP DETERMINE WHAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED. THE STATE POLICE DETERMINED THE PACKAGE CONTAINED RIFLE PROPELLED FALRES AND SEIZED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT TOGETHER WITH OUTER PACKAGING.
